00:49:01.270 --> 00:49:04.540
But what you see here on the
right-hand side is essentially,

00:49:04.540 --> 00:49:08.041
the interest rates are
something in the 1,000%.

00:49:08.041 --> 00:49:10.790
These are the annualized
interest rates.

00:49:10.790 --> 00:49:12.280
These are enormous
interest rates.

00:49:12.280 --> 00:49:16.180
Usually people take
many loans of that.

00:49:16.180 --> 00:49:17.560
They also take repeated loans.

00:49:17.560 --> 00:49:20.380
So it's not just as an emergency
where people take a loan,

00:49:20.380 --> 00:49:23.020
but people tend to roll over
these loans over and over

00:49:23.020 --> 00:49:25.540
again, and actually pay
lots and lots of money

00:49:25.540 --> 00:49:26.950
to these companies.

00:49:26.950 --> 00:49:30.370
There's often very
high credit card APRs,

00:49:30.370 --> 00:49:33.790
which 20%, 25%, and
so on are very common.

00:49:33.790 --> 00:49:36.160
Again, lots of people have
lots of credit card debt.

00:49:36.160 --> 00:49:38.590
And often, it's again, not
just to deal with shocks.

00:49:38.590 --> 00:49:39.760
You might say, well,
if you have a health

00:49:39.760 --> 00:49:41.530
shock or some other
shock in the family,

00:49:41.530 --> 00:49:44.960
if people get perhaps unemployed
for a short period of time,

00:49:44.960 --> 00:49:48.130
maybe that makes sense
to deal with that shock.

00:49:48.130 --> 00:49:51.160
But often, people
tend to roll over

00:49:51.160 --> 00:49:53.380
this interest for
many, many cycles,

00:49:53.380 --> 00:49:56.920
and keep paying these
really high interest rates.

00:49:56.920 --> 00:49:59.770
Now, in some sense, that's
just empirical evidence.

00:49:59.770 --> 00:50:02.030
That's just a fact that
these things exist.

00:50:02.030 --> 00:50:04.360
However, when you
think that through,

00:50:04.360 --> 00:50:08.210
you get very absurd implications
of this short-run impatience.

00:50:08.210 --> 00:50:10.630
So what I showed you now is
several pieces of evidence

00:50:10.630 --> 00:50:12.640
of short-run impatience.

00:50:12.640 --> 00:50:14.980
Now taking the exponential
discounting model

00:50:14.980 --> 00:50:16.960
very seriously, we're
going to think about some

00:50:16.960 --> 00:50:18.730
of these implications
of what does

00:50:18.730 --> 00:50:22.720
the exponential discounting
model say and imply from that.

00:50:22.720 --> 00:50:25.450
And one way to think
about this is the money

00:50:25.450 --> 00:50:26.770
now versus later choices.

00:50:26.770 --> 00:50:31.060
As I told you before, when
you look at number one here,

00:50:31.060 --> 00:50:32.560
I was asking you
about what makes

00:50:32.560 --> 00:50:35.890
you indifferent between $100
now and $X in two weeks.

00:50:35.890 --> 00:50:41.047
And the median student was
saying something $120, $115.

00:50:41.047 --> 00:50:42.880
And you can think about
what does that imply

00:50:42.880 --> 00:50:44.470
for the yearly delta.

00:50:44.470 --> 00:50:48.520
Well, it implies for the yearly
delta that it's about 5/6.

00:50:48.520 --> 00:50:50.260
So you're indifferent
between $100

00:50:50.260 --> 00:50:52.700
now versus $120 in the future.

00:50:52.700 --> 00:50:56.590
So that must mean the
future is 5/6 as much worth

00:50:56.590 --> 00:50:59.710
as the present is
for you right now.

00:50:59.710 --> 00:51:02.830
Now, that's fine.

00:51:02.830 --> 00:51:05.270
Excuse me, that
was the two weeks

00:51:05.270 --> 00:51:09.760
that was I was asking you
about, $100 now versus X

00:51:09.760 --> 00:51:11.190
dollars in 2 weeks from now.

00:51:11.190 --> 00:51:13.487
So the two-week delta is 5/6.

00:51:13.487 --> 00:51:15.070
Now you can think
about what does that

00:51:15.070 --> 00:51:18.310
mean for your four-week delta.

00:51:18.310 --> 00:51:20.050
Well, it's 5/6 to
the power of 2.

00:51:23.080 --> 00:51:25.930
So that's essentially you're
indifferent between $100 now

00:51:25.930 --> 00:51:28.600
and $144 in four weeks from now.

00:51:28.600 --> 00:51:31.000
You're also indifferent
between $100 now

00:51:31.000 --> 00:51:34.000
and $11,400 in a year from now.

00:51:34.000 --> 00:51:36.130
And you're also indifferent
between $100 now

00:51:36.130 --> 00:51:38.020
and I don't even know
what that number is,

00:51:38.020 --> 00:51:40.310
but a very, very large number.

00:51:40.310 --> 00:51:42.490
So if you think the
discount factor is delta,

00:51:42.490 --> 00:51:44.740
and you just roll
that forward, you

00:51:44.740 --> 00:51:46.510
get essentially
absurd implications,

00:51:46.510 --> 00:51:50.080
the reason being that we
assume the discount factor

00:51:50.080 --> 00:51:50.807
is constant.

00:51:50.807 --> 00:51:52.390
And so that, then,
essentially, if you

00:51:52.390 --> 00:51:56.440
are reasonably impatient
between the present and any time

00:51:56.440 --> 00:51:58.715
in the near future, like
two or four weeks from now,

00:51:58.715 --> 00:52:00.340
that must imply that
you really, really

00:52:00.340 --> 00:52:02.048
don't care about what's
happening in five

00:52:02.048 --> 00:52:04.820
years from now, and so on.

00:52:04.820 --> 00:52:07.210
Now, that's completely
unrealistic.

00:52:07.210 --> 00:52:09.512
The discount factor for
two-week delays in the future

00:52:09.512 --> 00:52:11.470
must be, in some ways,
higher than the discount

00:52:11.470 --> 00:52:13.220
factor for two-week
delays in the present.

00:52:13.220 --> 00:52:15.803
And that's essentially what the
quasi-hyperbolic, or the model

00:52:15.803 --> 00:52:17.830
I'm going to propose to
you in the next class,

00:52:17.830 --> 00:52:20.540
is going to try and explain.

00:52:20.540 --> 00:52:21.850
So why is that unrealistic?

00:52:21.850 --> 00:52:23.830
Well, we know for many
situations in the world,

00:52:23.830 --> 00:52:25.810
people care a lot
about the future.

00:52:25.810 --> 00:52:27.130
People save for retirement.

00:52:27.130 --> 00:52:28.540
People invest in education.

00:52:28.540 --> 00:52:29.830
People exercise, often.

00:52:29.830 --> 00:52:31.000
People do problem sets.

00:52:31.000 --> 00:52:32.260
People brush their teeth.

00:52:32.260 --> 00:52:33.760
People eat healthy, and so on.

00:52:33.760 --> 00:52:35.420
People invest a
lot in the future,

00:52:35.420 --> 00:52:38.620
in stuff that happens four
or five, six, seven, 10

00:52:38.620 --> 00:52:39.740
years from now.

00:52:39.740 --> 00:52:42.460
So they care a lot about
the future in some ways.

00:52:42.460 --> 00:52:44.750
Yet we find the
short-run impatience.

00:52:44.750 --> 00:52:49.930
So now we need to find some
model that can bridge this gap.

00:52:49.930 --> 00:52:52.780
And so another
way to put this is

00:52:52.780 --> 00:52:55.960
when you look at the evidence
that we have in terms

00:52:55.960 --> 00:52:58.780
of my time horizon, when
you look at discount

00:52:58.780 --> 00:53:02.350
factors conducted in
studies such as the one

00:53:02.350 --> 00:53:07.330
that I just showed you, or using
real-world decisions, what you

00:53:07.330 --> 00:53:10.060
see usually is that the discount
factor in the very short run

00:53:10.060 --> 00:53:12.880
tends to be very small.

00:53:12.880 --> 00:53:15.755
This is what you see on the
left-hand side of the graph.

00:53:15.755 --> 00:53:17.380
When you look at
further in the future,

00:53:17.380 --> 00:53:19.540
the discount factor
tends to be higher.

00:53:19.540 --> 00:53:22.330
Or another way to put this is
the estimated delta increases

00:53:22.330 --> 00:53:23.980
by time horizon.

00:53:23.980 --> 00:53:27.430
Again, that's a violation of the
exponential discounting model.

00:53:30.250 --> 00:53:32.000
So that's the first
piece of evidence.

00:53:32.000 --> 00:53:33.730
The second one is
preference reversal,

00:53:33.730 --> 00:53:35.370
dynamic inconsistency.

00:53:35.370 --> 00:53:37.120
What I mean by that
is dynamic consistency

00:53:37.120 --> 00:53:39.370
is essentially the
property that when

00:53:39.370 --> 00:53:42.850
you make a choice for the future
between two future periods,

00:53:42.850 --> 00:53:45.790
and when the future then
comes absent new information

00:53:45.790 --> 00:53:47.800
or any other things
that have happened,

00:53:47.800 --> 00:53:49.785
you will stick to that choice.

00:53:49.785 --> 00:53:51.160
A formal decision
or a definition

00:53:51.160 --> 00:53:52.750
here is, the action
a person thinks

00:53:52.750 --> 00:53:55.150
she should take in
the future always

00:53:55.150 --> 00:53:57.310
coincides with the action
that she actually prefers

00:53:57.310 --> 00:53:59.620
to take once the time comes.

00:53:59.620 --> 00:54:02.320
So if I make a plan
to exercise tomorrow,

00:54:02.320 --> 00:54:04.590
or if I make a plan
to eat salad tomorrow,

00:54:04.590 --> 00:54:05.840
I'm going to actually do that.

00:54:05.840 --> 00:54:08.080
I'm not going to be,
actually watching movies

00:54:08.080 --> 00:54:11.170
seems like a good idea, or
the potato chips instead

00:54:11.170 --> 00:54:12.550
look better.

00:54:12.550 --> 00:54:14.080
I have perfect
foresight in what I'm

00:54:14.080 --> 00:54:15.560
going to plan for the future.

00:54:15.560 --> 00:54:16.960
I know my future preferences.

00:54:16.960 --> 00:54:19.510
And my future preferences for
what I want for the future

00:54:19.510 --> 00:54:24.650
coincide with what I actually
want in the future, as well.

00:54:24.650 --> 00:54:28.390
And so put differently, there's
no intrapersonal conflicts.

00:54:28.390 --> 00:54:31.180
That is to say what I want
for the future is also

00:54:31.180 --> 00:54:35.810
what my future self
wants for itself.

00:54:35.810 --> 00:54:39.970
And so that's closely
connected to the assumption

00:54:39.970 --> 00:54:43.180
of exponential discounting--
that is to say exponential

00:54:43.180 --> 00:54:46.660
discounting has the assumption
that how much I care between

00:54:46.660 --> 00:54:49.270
the present and the
future is always--

00:54:49.270 --> 00:54:51.280
the weight is always
determined by delta,

00:54:51.280 --> 00:54:53.510
and that delta doesn't
change over time.

00:54:53.510 --> 00:54:55.240
So when I think now
about what I want

00:54:55.240 --> 00:54:57.400
in the future, between
a year from now

00:54:57.400 --> 00:54:59.110
and two years from
now, the difference

00:54:59.110 --> 00:55:01.900
between those or the discounting
will always be delta.

00:55:01.900 --> 00:55:04.390
Once the future
comes, the difference

00:55:04.390 --> 00:55:06.973
between a year from then and--

00:55:06.973 --> 00:55:08.890
at the time, then, it
will be like the present

00:55:08.890 --> 00:55:10.598
and a year from now--
will also be delta.

00:55:10.598 --> 00:55:12.800
So there's no difference there.

00:55:12.800 --> 00:55:15.370
So what's the formal argument
of the exponential discounting

00:55:15.370 --> 00:55:16.120
model?

00:55:16.120 --> 00:55:18.010
Well, it is essentially
if at time 0,

00:55:18.010 --> 00:55:19.983
I prefer an action
A over an action B,

00:55:19.983 --> 00:55:21.400
suppose there's
different actions.

00:55:21.400 --> 00:55:23.410
There's action A
and action B that I

00:55:23.410 --> 00:55:26.680
can do starting in period one.

00:55:26.680 --> 00:55:30.040
Well, if I prefer action A over
action B, on the left-hand side

00:55:30.040 --> 00:55:32.290
there's the utilities
associated with that.

00:55:32.290 --> 00:55:36.670
There's u0 plus delta
times u1 A of action

00:55:36.670 --> 00:55:41.050
A plus delta squared of
u2 of action A, and so on.

00:55:41.050 --> 00:55:43.150
If I prefer that over
action B, well, it

00:55:43.150 --> 00:55:45.100
must be that I prefer
the stream of utility

00:55:45.100 --> 00:55:47.590
on the left-hand side
to the stream of utility

00:55:47.590 --> 00:55:49.780
on the right-hand side.

00:55:49.780 --> 00:55:53.140
But now that implies if I take
away the u0, because they're

00:55:53.140 --> 00:55:55.030
the same on both
sides, because I'm

00:55:55.030 --> 00:55:59.210
making choices for the future,
and then divide by delta, what

00:55:59.210 --> 00:56:05.740
I get is essentially, again, an
equality that at time 1, again,

00:56:05.740 --> 00:56:11.600
I still prefer option A over
option B. That is to say,

00:56:11.600 --> 00:56:13.720
if I prefer option
A over option B

00:56:13.720 --> 00:56:15.910
at time 0, that
implies essentially

00:56:15.910 --> 00:56:20.395
that I also prefer option
A over option B at time 1.

00:56:20.395 --> 00:56:22.270
So that essentially is
another way to say it,

00:56:22.270 --> 00:56:25.030
is that the exponential
discounting factor

00:56:25.030 --> 00:56:28.610
implies time and consistency.

00:56:28.610 --> 00:56:29.750
Any questions about that?

00:56:41.630 --> 00:56:43.962
So what examples do we have
that violate this property?

00:56:43.962 --> 00:56:46.420
We already talked about this
a bit in the previous classes,

00:56:46.420 --> 00:56:49.162
but just remind ourselves.

00:56:54.090 --> 00:56:55.930
Yes.

00:56:55.930 --> 00:56:57.640
STUDENT: The betting
on how much weight

00:56:57.640 --> 00:56:59.280
you lose when you're on a diet.

00:56:59.280 --> 00:57:04.988
You make sure that you'll
want to change your behavior.

00:57:04.988 --> 00:57:06.030
FRANK SCHILBACH: Exactly.

00:57:06.030 --> 00:57:08.880
So dieting in general seems
a great example of saying,

00:57:08.880 --> 00:57:11.010
I really would like
to lose some weight,

00:57:11.010 --> 00:57:12.870
or have some target
weight, or some target

00:57:12.870 --> 00:57:14.910
exercising, or a certain
behavior of eating

00:57:14.910 --> 00:57:16.900
and exercising or combined.

00:57:16.900 --> 00:57:18.900
And I really would
like to do that.

00:57:18.900 --> 00:57:20.940
For now-- I mean, I
think about the future.

00:57:20.940 --> 00:57:23.118
Often at New Year's
or certain points

00:57:23.118 --> 00:57:24.660
of the year, our
birthdays and so on,

00:57:24.660 --> 00:57:26.460
people think, OK,
I'm going to do this.

00:57:26.460 --> 00:57:27.870
I have great plans and so on.

00:57:27.870 --> 00:57:29.880
They have certain
preferences for the future.

00:57:29.880 --> 00:57:32.340
But then the future comes a
week or a month from then.

00:57:32.340 --> 00:57:35.310
People don't follow through.

00:57:35.310 --> 00:57:35.850
Exactly.

00:57:35.850 --> 00:57:37.590
That's essentially
a clear example

00:57:37.590 --> 00:57:40.050
of a preference reversal,
which is essentially

00:57:40.050 --> 00:57:42.540
another way of
saying preferences

00:57:42.540 --> 00:57:44.220
are dynamically inconsistent.

00:57:49.310 --> 00:57:50.585
Any other example?

00:58:13.970 --> 00:58:15.316
Yes.

00:58:15.316 --> 00:58:17.534
STUDENT: [INAUDIBLE]
say we should

00:58:17.534 --> 00:58:19.753
do something, kind of
like this is, like,

00:58:19.753 --> 00:58:22.218
what we want our future to be.

00:58:22.218 --> 00:58:24.808
[INAUDIBLE]

00:58:24.808 --> 00:58:25.850
FRANK SCHILBACH: Exactly.

00:58:25.850 --> 00:58:28.627
So that's true for,
did you say exercising?

00:58:28.627 --> 00:58:29.210
STUDENT: Yeah.

00:58:29.210 --> 00:58:32.480
FRANK SCHILBACH: Yeah,
for exercising, exactly.

00:58:32.480 --> 00:58:35.660
I'll show you some examples of
people, for example, signing up

00:58:35.660 --> 00:58:37.770
for gyms that pay
yearly membership fees,

00:58:37.770 --> 00:58:40.250
and so on, that tend
to be very expensive.

00:58:40.250 --> 00:58:41.750
The idea often is
then they think

00:58:41.750 --> 00:58:46.910
about they will go to the gym
weekly, or daily, or whatever.

00:58:46.910 --> 00:58:49.850
And then under that assumption
for your preferences

00:58:49.850 --> 00:58:52.650
for the future, then it
makes a lot of sense.

00:58:52.650 --> 00:58:55.298
But then if you then
not actually go,

00:58:55.298 --> 00:58:56.840
or if your preferences
are different,

00:58:56.840 --> 00:58:59.240
then it turns out to be
different in the future, that's

00:58:59.240 --> 00:59:01.070
a pretty bad idea.

00:59:01.070 --> 00:59:03.130
Yes, you were saying.

00:59:03.130 --> 00:59:06.093
STUDENT: So consider
apples or bananas.

00:59:06.093 --> 00:59:08.873
If I'm choosing [INAUDIBLE].

00:59:17.420 --> 00:59:19.430
FRANK SCHILBACH:
Yeah, to be clear,

00:59:19.430 --> 00:59:22.610
if you just start eating
apples because you

00:59:22.610 --> 00:59:24.658
had too many bananas
in the past, that's

00:59:24.658 --> 00:59:25.950
not what we were talking about.

00:59:25.950 --> 00:59:29.900
So it's not about
people's past choices

00:59:29.900 --> 00:59:32.900
affecting future choices through
some form of habit formation,

00:59:32.900 --> 00:59:35.450
or people getting bored,
or tired, or the like.

00:59:35.450 --> 00:59:38.150
But it's about if I today
choose today I want bananas,

00:59:38.150 --> 00:59:42.380
tomorrow I want apples, and then
tomorrow I'm actually saying,

00:59:42.380 --> 00:59:45.950
actually, I don't like
apples, I really like bananas,

00:59:45.950 --> 00:59:47.262
then that would be a violation.

00:59:47.262 --> 00:59:49.220
But it needs to be
something that's essentially

00:59:49.220 --> 00:59:54.440
either new information or
some new options or so on that

00:59:54.440 --> 00:59:56.637
become available.

00:59:56.637 --> 00:59:58.220
In the example that
you're mentioning,

00:59:58.220 --> 00:59:59.360
there was none of that.

00:59:59.360 --> 01:00:02.600
So that's not quite what
we're talking about.

01:00:02.600 --> 01:00:05.700
More common is-- and there's a
paper that does this, in fact,

01:00:05.700 --> 01:00:08.720
with Dutch employees by Read
and van Leeuwen that essentially

01:00:08.720 --> 01:00:10.630
asked people about
next week first.

01:00:10.630 --> 01:00:12.350
So it asked them
about-- this is actually

01:00:12.350 --> 01:00:15.618
an actual company, where
workers were asked, after lunch,

01:00:15.618 --> 01:00:16.910
would you like to have a snack?

01:00:16.910 --> 01:00:18.950
And what snack would
you like to have?

01:00:18.950 --> 01:00:21.690
Would you like to have
apples or chocolate?

01:00:21.690 --> 01:00:24.930
When you're asked to do
that today for next week,

01:00:24.930 --> 01:00:27.940
74% chose fruit or
apples, essentially.

01:00:27.940 --> 01:00:31.020
So lots of people tend to want
to be virtuous in the future,

01:00:31.020 --> 01:00:32.580
eat healthily, and so on.

01:00:32.580 --> 01:00:34.330
When you ask them then
the same question--

01:00:34.330 --> 01:00:36.930
so then in the actual
experiment, what

01:00:36.930 --> 01:00:39.840
they did is then they went
back to the workers, and said,

01:00:39.840 --> 01:00:41.080
oh, I forgot your choice.

01:00:41.080 --> 01:00:43.420
Why don't you choose again.

01:00:43.420 --> 01:00:44.190
Let us know.

01:00:44.190 --> 01:00:46.530
That was a little bit
cheating, but then essentially,

01:00:46.530 --> 01:00:52.620
70% of people, when it comes for
the same day, choose chocolate.

01:00:52.620 --> 01:00:54.870
And here's none of
that, in the sense

01:00:54.870 --> 01:00:56.970
of there's no habit
formation, there's

01:00:56.970 --> 01:00:59.233
no people ate too many
apples and now they

01:00:59.233 --> 01:01:00.150
really want chocolate.

01:01:00.150 --> 01:01:01.680
That was only one choice.

01:01:01.680 --> 01:01:03.510
And so now, when I
make some choices

01:01:03.510 --> 01:01:05.340
for the future and
the future comes,

01:01:05.340 --> 01:01:09.310
I should stick to that choice.

01:01:09.310 --> 01:01:11.450
Similarly, there's
movie choices.

01:01:11.450 --> 01:01:13.210
It used to be--

01:01:13.210 --> 01:01:15.490
you guys are probably
too young for this--

01:01:15.490 --> 01:01:19.647
Netflix used to send
you movies to your home.

01:01:19.647 --> 01:01:21.730
But often what lots of
people had was this issue--

01:01:21.730 --> 01:01:25.180
they had great plans of watching
highbrow, or high culture,

01:01:25.180 --> 01:01:31.005
and often sad or deep
movies in the future.

01:01:31.005 --> 01:01:32.380
There's really
things they wanted

01:01:32.380 --> 01:01:34.480
to watch, be it The
Piano or Schindler's List

01:01:34.480 --> 01:01:37.280
and so on, which
by some category

01:01:37.280 --> 01:01:38.560
we might call highbrow.

01:01:38.560 --> 01:01:40.690
But instead, when
the present comes,

01:01:40.690 --> 01:01:44.230
people often like to watch
essentially lowbrow movies

01:01:44.230 --> 01:01:46.870
like comedies, and
so on and so forth,

01:01:46.870 --> 01:01:50.080
for example, Four Weddings and
a Funeral, Speed, and so on,

01:01:50.080 --> 01:01:51.538
so action movies or the like.

01:01:51.538 --> 01:01:53.080
And then what would
happen in Netflix

01:01:53.080 --> 01:01:55.930
often is you would get all
these movies that you'd really

01:01:55.930 --> 01:01:59.710
love to watch in the future,
but never in the present,

01:01:59.710 --> 01:02:01.720
then get stuck with them.

01:02:01.720 --> 01:02:03.970
And there's, in fact,
an example or a paper

01:02:03.970 --> 01:02:06.530
who does this, which essentially
elicits people's preferences

01:02:06.530 --> 01:02:08.530
for what they would like
to watch in the present

01:02:08.530 --> 01:02:09.880
versus in the future.

01:02:09.880 --> 01:02:11.350
And what you see,
essentially, is

01:02:11.350 --> 01:02:14.140
people tend to
systematically pick

01:02:14.140 --> 01:02:16.270
for the present,
for tonight, people

01:02:16.270 --> 01:02:19.360
tend to watch or want
to watch lowbrow movies.

01:02:19.360 --> 01:02:22.990
Action, rom com, or whatever
sounds really good for tonight.

01:02:22.990 --> 01:02:25.610
When you think about what would
you like to watch next week,

01:02:25.610 --> 01:02:28.660
people tend to pick
highbrow movies instead.

01:02:32.690 --> 01:02:37.040
And there's lots of
examples of that kind.

01:02:37.040 --> 01:02:39.350
And so just to summarize,
these preference reversals,

01:02:39.350 --> 01:02:41.870
again, these are not really
possible in the exponential

01:02:41.870 --> 01:02:43.070
discounting model.

01:02:43.070 --> 01:02:44.070
That should not occur.

01:02:44.070 --> 01:02:46.643
That's by assumption not
possible in that model,

01:02:46.643 --> 01:02:48.560
as I just showed you
before, yet we see plenty

01:02:48.560 --> 01:02:51.120
of examples in the real world.

01:02:51.120 --> 01:02:54.110
Now, the third piece of evidence
is demand for commitment.

01:02:54.110 --> 01:02:56.670
That's really closely
related to that.

01:02:56.670 --> 01:02:59.000
So one example here is
demand for commitment

01:02:59.000 --> 01:03:02.960
is essentially when you know
that your future preferences

01:03:02.960 --> 01:03:05.360
will be different from
your present preferences,

01:03:05.360 --> 01:03:07.740
you might engage in
commitment devices.

01:03:07.740 --> 01:03:08.900
What does that mean?

01:03:08.900 --> 01:03:11.957
You might want to change
the prices of your options

01:03:11.957 --> 01:03:12.540
in the future.

01:03:12.540 --> 01:03:14.415
And particularly, you
might want to take away

01:03:14.415 --> 01:03:16.760
some options in the future.

01:03:16.760 --> 01:03:20.420
One example is Ulysses
and the Sirens.

01:03:20.420 --> 01:03:23.300
Who knows that story or
can tell me what it is?

01:03:23.300 --> 01:03:24.149
Yes.

01:03:24.149 --> 01:03:28.061
STUDENT: So basically,
there are these Sirens,

01:03:28.061 --> 01:03:35.396
and they're singing
and [INAUDIBLE]..

01:03:35.396 --> 01:03:45.070
But [INAUDIBLE] but it's hard to
tear yourself from [INAUDIBLE]..

01:03:45.070 --> 01:03:49.552
So he had [INAUDIBLE]
tied to the ship

01:03:49.552 --> 01:03:51.490
so that he wouldn't be able to.

01:03:51.490 --> 01:03:52.760
FRANK SCHILBACH: Yes, exactly.

01:03:52.760 --> 01:03:53.510
So here's Ulysses.

01:03:53.510 --> 01:03:57.070
I think he was on his way
back from his long journey.

01:03:59.950 --> 01:04:03.070
He knew that the Sirens
were going to come.

01:04:03.070 --> 01:04:05.500
He knew that his preferences
would change in the future--

01:04:05.500 --> 01:04:07.190
that he would not
be able to resist

01:04:07.190 --> 01:04:10.120
their power or their songs.

01:04:10.120 --> 01:04:12.880
And so what he did
is he asked his crew

01:04:12.880 --> 01:04:15.070
to bind him to the
mast so he would not

01:04:15.070 --> 01:04:18.672
be able to leave the ship, even
if he wanted to in the future.

01:04:18.672 --> 01:04:21.130
And that's demand for commitment
because he was taking away

01:04:21.130 --> 01:04:24.100
some options in the
future, with a goal

01:04:24.100 --> 01:04:27.040
to change his future behavior,
knowing that his preferences

01:04:27.040 --> 01:04:29.800
would change in the future.

01:04:29.800 --> 01:04:32.290
If you wonder why the
guys who are rowing

01:04:32.290 --> 01:04:33.430
are not leaving the ship.

01:04:33.430 --> 01:04:35.320
They had wax in their ears.

01:04:35.320 --> 01:04:38.090
I don't know why Ulysses
couldn't use the wax either,

01:04:38.090 --> 01:04:41.080
but anyway--

01:04:41.080 --> 01:04:43.060
So that's one example
of a commitment device.

01:04:43.060 --> 01:04:45.310
There's another one, which
is sort of financial advice

01:04:45.310 --> 01:04:47.890
that people often get,
which is the following--

01:04:47.890 --> 01:04:51.100
cut up your credit card
and store the cards.

01:04:51.100 --> 01:04:55.360
If possible, get rid of
all your credit cards

01:04:55.360 --> 01:04:57.040
or put temptation out of reach.

01:04:57.040 --> 01:04:59.230
If you really can't do
without a credit card,

01:04:59.230 --> 01:05:00.340
limit yourself to one.

01:05:00.340 --> 01:05:03.080
Put it in a tub of water,
and stick it in the freezer.

01:05:03.080 --> 01:05:05.380
And so the idea here
is if you really

01:05:05.380 --> 01:05:09.640
have self-control
problems, well,

01:05:09.640 --> 01:05:11.920
when you want to buy
something really quickly,

01:05:11.920 --> 01:05:13.660
when temptation
sort of takes over,

01:05:13.660 --> 01:05:16.418
you have to limit your
options in some ways.

01:05:16.418 --> 01:05:18.460
So in some sense, have
you some cool down period.

01:05:18.460 --> 01:05:21.498
It takes a while to get your
credit card out of the freezer.

01:05:21.498 --> 01:05:22.040
I don't know.

01:05:22.040 --> 01:05:23.635
I asked my wife about
is this a thing?

01:05:23.635 --> 01:05:25.510
And she was saying,
well, haven't you watched

01:05:25.510 --> 01:05:27.070
"Confessions of a Shopaholic?"

01:05:27.070 --> 01:05:28.150
I have not.

01:05:28.150 --> 01:05:30.130
If you want to watch
that video, you

01:05:30.130 --> 01:05:33.490
see, in fact, apparently
that is, in fact, a thing.

01:05:33.490 --> 01:05:36.920
But the idea of having
some cool down period,

01:05:36.920 --> 01:05:39.770
which essentially is to
deal with essentially

01:05:39.770 --> 01:05:42.430
short-run impatience,
comes in many settings

01:05:42.430 --> 01:05:43.390
and many variations.

01:05:43.390 --> 01:05:45.940
In fact, for example, if
you'd like to get married,

01:05:45.940 --> 01:05:48.610
often you have to
go to some office

01:05:48.610 --> 01:05:51.023
and declare that you would
like to get married, and then

01:05:51.023 --> 01:05:52.690
wait for another three
days or something

01:05:52.690 --> 01:05:54.370
until you actually get married.

01:05:54.370 --> 01:05:58.450
Often, the idea is people
sometimes come to their senses

01:05:58.450 --> 01:06:00.640
and it takes a few days.

01:06:06.250 --> 01:06:08.410
So what do these examples show?

01:06:08.410 --> 01:06:10.450
Well, they show that
people have a tendency

01:06:10.450 --> 01:06:12.010
for immediate gratification.

01:06:12.010 --> 01:06:17.530
And they tend to
discount quite heavily

01:06:17.530 --> 01:06:19.665
in short-term decisions.

01:06:19.665 --> 01:06:21.790
Now, what does the demand
for commitment then show?

01:06:21.790 --> 01:06:26.230
It's we, in fact, tend to
disapprove of this tendency

01:06:26.230 --> 01:06:27.460
beforehand.

01:06:27.460 --> 01:06:29.210
That is to say we know
that in the future,

01:06:29.210 --> 01:06:30.400
we might be impatient.

01:06:30.400 --> 01:06:31.730
We don't like that.

01:06:31.730 --> 01:06:34.030
And because of that, we
bind ourselves to the mast,

01:06:34.030 --> 01:06:38.950
or we freeze our credit cards,
or some people, at least, do.

01:06:41.630 --> 01:06:43.090
And so all of these
decision makers

01:06:43.090 --> 01:06:44.507
are time inconsistent
in the sense

01:06:44.507 --> 01:06:48.945
that when they make certain
choices for the future, what

01:06:48.945 --> 01:06:51.320
they will want to choose in
the future will be different.

01:06:51.320 --> 01:06:54.040
And knowing that, they will
restrict their options.

01:06:54.040 --> 01:06:59.830
That is to say, different
selves want different things.

01:06:59.830 --> 01:07:03.030
So then what's the
heart of the issue?

01:07:03.030 --> 01:07:04.780
Well, the heart of the
issue is that there

01:07:04.780 --> 01:07:07.533
are conflicts rooted between
short and long-run patience.

01:07:07.533 --> 01:07:09.700
What we want in the short
run is different from what

01:07:09.700 --> 01:07:10.868
we want in the long run.

01:07:10.868 --> 01:07:12.910
That is to say when we
think ahead of the future,

01:07:12.910 --> 01:07:14.050
we tend to be very patient.

01:07:14.050 --> 01:07:17.810
There's all sorts of good things
we want to do in the future.

01:07:17.810 --> 01:07:19.420
When the time
actually comes, when

01:07:19.420 --> 01:07:22.728
we think about the present,
we tend to be impatient.

01:07:22.728 --> 01:07:24.520
Now the issue with
exponential discounting,

01:07:24.520 --> 01:07:27.400
then, is the exponential
discounting model

01:07:27.400 --> 01:07:29.980
has only one parameter
which captures

01:07:29.980 --> 01:07:32.260
essentially discounting.

01:07:32.260 --> 01:07:33.700
But it can sort of--

01:07:33.700 --> 01:07:35.710
by assumption, the
discounting needs

01:07:35.710 --> 01:07:38.080
to be the same across
all time horizons.

01:07:38.080 --> 01:07:41.350
That is to say, it can only
match one of those two things,

01:07:41.350 --> 01:07:42.520
but not both.

01:07:42.520 --> 01:07:45.820
It can only match either your
short-run discounting, but then

01:07:45.820 --> 01:07:47.610
the long-run discounting
is off, or you

01:07:47.610 --> 01:07:49.360
can try to match the
long-run discounting,

01:07:49.360 --> 01:07:51.220
but then the short-run
discounting is off.

01:07:51.220 --> 01:07:54.670
So what that tells us,
we need two parameters

01:07:54.670 --> 01:07:57.640
to deal with that.

01:07:57.640 --> 01:07:59.440
So what we want, and
I'll talk about this

01:07:59.440 --> 01:08:02.570
a lot more in the next class
or in the next few minutes.

01:08:02.570 --> 01:08:04.510
And then in the next
class, we want a model

01:08:04.510 --> 01:08:07.480
that has greater patience
for trade-offs in the future

01:08:07.480 --> 01:08:09.700
than for trade-offs
in the present.

01:08:09.700 --> 01:08:12.130
And then we want another model.

01:08:12.130 --> 01:08:14.860
So one is we want different
levels of patience

01:08:14.860 --> 01:08:17.020
over different time
horizons, and we

01:08:17.020 --> 01:08:19.240
want a model that
explains or helps us

01:08:19.240 --> 01:08:21.819
explain dynamic inconsistency.

01:08:21.819 --> 01:08:23.430
So what is that model?

01:08:23.430 --> 01:08:26.937
So I just showed you before the
exponential discounting model.

01:08:26.937 --> 01:08:28.479
That's just what I
showed you before,

01:08:28.479 --> 01:08:30.970
but that's exactly the
same, where essentially,

01:08:30.970 --> 01:08:35.470
your discounted or lifetime
utility is essentially

01:08:35.470 --> 01:08:37.779
what's given here,
where we have delta.

01:08:37.779 --> 01:08:39.100
It's between 0 and 1.

01:08:39.100 --> 01:08:41.229
And delta is a short-term
discount factor

01:08:41.229 --> 01:08:43.479
and it's a long-run
discount factor.

01:08:43.479 --> 01:08:47.109
If I'm trying to decide
between t and t plus 1,

01:08:47.109 --> 01:08:49.300
the difference between
that is essentially delta.

01:08:49.300 --> 01:08:51.939
And if I decide between
t plus 3 and t plus 4,

01:08:51.939 --> 01:08:55.569
it's also delta that
regulates this factor.

01:08:55.569 --> 01:08:57.880
Now, what does the
quasi-hyperbolic discounting

01:08:57.880 --> 01:08:58.510
model do?

01:08:58.510 --> 01:09:00.399
It has another parameter.

01:09:00.399 --> 01:09:02.800
And this parameter
is called beta.

01:09:02.800 --> 01:09:06.970
And beta governs, essentially,
short-run discounting,

01:09:06.970 --> 01:09:09.640
while delta is the
long-run discount factor.

01:09:09.640 --> 01:09:11.290
What is that telling us?

01:09:11.290 --> 01:09:15.170
Essentially, beta discounts
anything that's in the future.

01:09:15.170 --> 01:09:17.380
So essentially, if you
look at the equation now,

01:09:17.380 --> 01:09:20.050
anything that's in the
future, that's not period t,

01:09:20.050 --> 01:09:22.520
is discounted by beta.

01:09:22.520 --> 01:09:24.350
And then within
any future periods,

01:09:24.350 --> 01:09:26.562
we have another discount
factor that's essentially

